[5
Date: 6 Mar 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: MAFF [edited

Farmers desperate to move livestock free of the disease have been granted
special licences to take their animals to abattoirs. But the number of
qualifying farms is dwindling, as 76 cases of foot-and-mouth have been
confirmed in Britain.
Since the ban on livestock movement was imposed 11 days ago, healthy
animals have been stuck on farms losing value. Farmers have been rushing to
apply for the licences. In Aberdeenshire alone 71 licences have been
applied for. But those living within 6 miles of an affected area cannot apply.
Vets from as far away as Australia and Canada [and USA have been drafted
in to help trace thousands of animals, including 100 000 sheep. [Providing
them with much needed hands-on experience. - Mod.MHJ
In France all movement of sheep, pigs, goats, and horses has been banned
for 2 weeks.
But EU Consumer Protection Commissioner David Byrne has insisted the
current crisis was still short of epidemic proportions and has ruled out a
European-wide vaccination program to prevent the spread of the disease.
Such a program would involve vaccinating 300 million animals every 6 months
and would make it impossible to distinguish between livestock which had
been immunized and those which had contracted the disease.
Mr Byrne told BBC Radio 4's Today program: "You would then debilitate the
value of your livestock herds throughout the European Union and lose the
opportunity of trading on the world-wide market." But he did say there was
a case for using limited vaccination programs as a "fire wall" to control
outbreaks and 30 million vaccinations were available.
Checks are continuing to see if the disease has spread to free-ranging
livestock on Dartmoor after an outbreak at a local farm. Government vets
said they believe the outbreak, at the Duchy of Cornwall farm inside the
national park in Devon, is linked to previous cases. But if it is not
linked, it could mean that up to 40 000 cattle and sheep on the moor would
have to be culled. The Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (MAFF)
said it had ruled out a cull of the Dartmoor ponies.
­­
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Some 30 years ago L.P. Smith and I did a paper exercise on the potential
benefits of using vaccination to stop FMD using 5 outbreaks in the previous
10 years. It utilized various "fire wall" responses. In 4 of these models,
vaccination would have added significantly to the problems and expense and
made no difference to the total number of herds affected. The fifth
involved not unusual numbers, but was linear in time (if I remember
correctly, it was spread over many weeks, even months) and only then might
vaccination have significantly reduced the number of herds affected. From
what I have seen of this epidemic, a "fire wall" campaign would not have
had any benefits and would certainly have presented many long-term costs.
Seen in historical context, this epidemic has had somewhat more outbreaks
than might be expected; but considering the epidemiological pattern
utilizing markets it is modest, thanks to the outstanding efforts of the
MAFF vets and others. - Mod.MHJ
